snippet.textDisplay:
The story is based on a folktale from Sindh, Pakistan, called "Umar Marvi." It revolves around a village girl named Marvi, belonging to the Phanwar tribe, who resists the advances of a powerful king named Umar and the allure of living in the palace as his queen. Instead, she chooses to remain in her simple rural environment, staying true to her village.

King Umar was deeply in love with Marvi due to her exceptional beauty. However, he forcefully took her and desired to marry her. He imprisoned her in his castle called Umerkot in Sindh. Marvi, being a woman of great integrity and honor, refused the king's offer, even though he promised to grant her every desire. She steadfastly denied everything and even went on a hunger strike while locked up. She declared that she would rather die than be disloyal.

Ultimately, the king had to give in to her unwavering loyalty. He released her and respectfully sent her back to her village, where she was hailed as a heroine. This remarkable story is depicted in the song "Aayi Aayi," where Marvi finally enjoys a simple meal at home. The peacock in the song symbolizes this act, while the dolphins represent the majestic Indus River (Sindh).

snippet.textDisplay:
Must say initially did not get the concept, then I went to BTS, upon just second watch,  fell in love with everything. The music, colours, vibrancy, valour and vivacity of the beautiful , ethnically rich and culturally diverse Sindhi folks took my breath away.
The fact that the song is a tribute to Marvi, whilst celebrating the arrival of CSP season 15, and encouraging strength and resilience in for form of 'Here she comes victorious' is superb.
Thanks for introducing us to the great vocalists, who I would love to hear more of, the colour palette of Sindh which I would love to incorporate (Punjabi here) and the cultural richness of Sindh which I'd love to see scattered all across Pakistan, and beyond.
Thanks for keeping the production predominantly Sindhi when it comes to music instruments and arrangements, though clearly the fusion with modern music and instruments makes it a song for every one.
Shukriya CSP! Keep winning 💕

"O bhai ! Kis ki tareef ki Jaye?" I mean who to admire ? is it Noman Rajpar who wrote the song , is it Xulfi & A.siidiqi , Saira vohra who didn't spare a single cultural thing and arrangements of thar, Fatima butt for the original colours of thar costumes Ovaise Gohar for capturing each frame with briliance par excellence AND OH MY GOOD LORD the voices of Saiba and Marvi having the true the real essence of 'Thar' sand. It's a 💯% team Marvel (forgive me for not writing all the names)
Now the video.  The first 40 silent seconds truly depicts the trauma 'Mai Marvi' passed through. The  girl wearing black dress on her 'Thari Existance' portrays Marvi is WOW ("Bhai kis nay itna zabardast intekhab kia?") The womam walking bare foot on sand to receive Marvi and welcome her with the eyes almost like stone in Marvi's wait then Marvi with a silent face and her friends in various colours. Peacock is considered as a family member in thar culture, the drinking water of the Peacock was soul shaking as he is breaking his 'fast' 'warat' which he observe in Marvi's separation (Judai)
"Koi kitna likhay"❤
